# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afl-commission
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] The **1897 VFL season** was the inaugural season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] The season ran from 8 May to 4 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a three-week finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] Eight Victorian Football Association (VFA) clubs – Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne, South Melbourne and St Kilda – featured in the inaugural season after seceding from the VFA in 1896.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] Essendon won the inaugural premiership after winning all three of its finals matches, with Geelong finishing as runners-up with two wins.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] Geelong won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James and Melbourne's Jack Leith tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] In 1897, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] Each team played each other twice in a home-and-away season of 14 rounds.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] Once the 14-round home-and-away season had finished, the 1897 VFL Premiers were determined according to the conditions dictated by the specific format and conventions of the 1897 Finals System, which was used in this season only.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] The following table can be sorted from biggest winning margin to biggest losing margin for each round.
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] If two or more matches in a round are decided by the same margin, these margins are sorted by percentage (i.e. the lowest-scoring winning team is ranked highest and the lowest-scoring losing team is ranked lowest).
[src:afl-commission/1897-vfl-season] Opponents are listed above the margins and home matches are in bold.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The **1898 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Essendon Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held in Melbourne on 24 September 1898.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match was played to determine the premiers for the 1898 VFL season.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The game was played under atrocious ground conditions in front of 16,538 people at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match is recognised as the first VFL grand final, although the term "grand final" was not in wide use until 1931.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] It was the first time that Victorian Football League premiership was decided in a final match, as the 1897 premiership was won under a different finals system by Essendon when they finished above three other clubs on the finals series ladder.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both Fitzroy back pocket Stan Reid and the Essendon full-forward Charlie Moore later died in South Africa in active service during the Anglo-Boer War—Moore on 5 May 1901, and Reid on 23 June 1901.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] During the 1898 home-and-away season, all teams played each other twice.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The winners of the two sections were Fitzroy and Collingwood, respectively (for results of all of the round-robin matches); and, a week later (17 September 1898), the two teams played each other at Brunswick Street Oval, with Fitzroy winning the match 2.10 (22) to 1.5 (11).
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] After the VFL referred the decision to the VFL's Match Arrangement Committee, they, upon the express instructions of that committee, rejected the suggestions of the two teams outright and the match was controversially scheduled to be played at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The Junction Oval was in an appalling condition, as the ground had not been used since the second Saturday of the sectional round-robin match three weeks earlier (3 September); and, since then, it had been thoroughly top-dressed and "cultivated" in anticipation of the coming cricket season.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Also, the cricket ground's asphalt cycling track that lay between the boundary line and the fence presented a considerable danger to the footballers.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Despite being the "challenger", Essendon flatly refused to play in the scheduled match, declaring that it would rather forfeit the match and the premiership than play on such a dangerous surface.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] This view was also strongly supported by Fitzroy, whose captain, Alec Sloan, had also taken the step of signing a statutory declaration to the effect that, in his opinion, the ground was entirely unfit to play on.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The VFL, perhaps somewhat driven by the fact that the attraction of a finals system was one of the major reasons that the eight teams had left the VFA and formed the VFL in the first place, had a special meeting to hear Essendon's appeal.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] While it chose to endorse the committee's decision, it also did everything it could to convince Essendon to play the match.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon did not actually agree to play the match until the night before the game; ultimately, this "in-doubt-until-the-last-minute match" was still attended by 16,538 paying spectators; it certainly would have been a much larger crowd otherwise.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] The ground had been in such a dreadful condition that, in the week prior to the match, over 40 dray-loads of rubbish, soil and street-sweepings had been taken from the ground.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] All of this last-minute work greatly improved the playing surface at the ground, with sportswriters noting that while the ground was imperfect, it was nevertheless fit for use.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Dry, windy weather and patches of ground where the topsoil had not bound meant that players often fell on the grassless slippery ground for want of some sort of grip, and play was often impeded by clouds of dust.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] To prevent any repeat of the events leading up to the 1898 challenge final, the VFL agreed that from 1899 they would schedule for a possible challenge final in advance.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] In 1898, all VFL teams had 20 on-the-field players and no "reserves".
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Although there were no reserves, any player who had left the playing field for any reason at all could resume his place on the field at any time.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy selected a set of brothers in its team: Jim and Mick Grace (see TALK page).
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon had beaten Fitzroy in their round 1 and round 8 matches by 53 and 43 points, respectively.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had beaten Essendon by 29 points in the third match of their round-robin Sectional matches.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both teams had great difficulty playing football in the appalling ground conditions—as evidenced by the low scores—and the tough, bustling Fitzroy team handled the conditions far better than the Essendon team that had hoped to spread the game out as far as possible.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy took the lead in the first few minutes of the match, and Essendon were never able to catch up.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon were further demoralized when Fitzroy champion forward and follower Mick Grace, renowned for his marking skill and kicking prowess, flew high over a pack to take a spectacular high mark and kicked a long-range goal.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] In a very tight, defensive second half, as the playing conditions deteriorated even further, only one goal was scored.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy went on to beat Essendon 5.8 (38) to 3.5 (23).
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] The **1898 VFL season** was the second season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 14 May to 24 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating Essendon by 15 points in the 1898 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] Essendon won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] Collingwood's Archie Smith won the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] In 1898, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1898 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] The VFL introduced a new system of finals for the 1898 season.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] The new system, which was used from 1898–1900, allowed all clubs to compete for the major premiership, with the minor premiers having the right to challenge for the premiership.
[src:afl-commission/1898-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Essendon won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] It was the second annual grand final of the Victorian Football League.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 4,823 spectators, was won by Fitzroy by a margin of 1 point, becoming the first club to claim back-to-back VFL premierships.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had won the minor premiership in the 1899 season, while South Melbourne had finished sixth after the home-and-away season.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] In the sectional major rounds, Fitzroy and South Melbourne each finished with records of 3–0 to qualify for the final.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Under the finals system in place, this match was the final of the major round, played between the two section winners.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Had South Melbourne won the match, it would not have immediately won the season's premiership; Fitzroy, as the minor premiers, would have had the right to challenge South to a rematch for the premiership on the following Saturday.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Meanwhile, Fitzroy could clinch the premiership win a win in this match.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] "The last match of the season for the league premiership was played on Saturday, when Fitzroy and South Melbourne met on the St.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Unfortunately, steady rain, which had fallen all the morning, continued nearly all the afternoon, making the conditions under which the game was played unsatisfactory for the players and most unpleasant for spectators.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] The "weather committee" had not met to consider the advisability of a postponement, and when the teams assembled South Melbourne suggested deferring the match until next Saturday, but Fitzroy preferred to brave the elements.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] The assembling of about 4000 spectators in the unfavorable circumstances indicated clearly that, if the weather had kept fine, the attendance would have been enormous.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] As it was, those present evinced keen interest in the game, every notable bit of good play being heartily cheered.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Amongst the onlookers were a number of enthusiasts from Geelong, who came up by special train.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] had the ground in splendid order until the rain came, and even after the steady downpour, extending over many hours, it played very, much better than could have been expected, reflecting great credit on the experienced and skilful curator. ...
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] The strong wind from the southern end of the ground favoured South Melbourne in the opening quarter.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Harry Lampe kicked the first two goals of the match, and Fitzroy's only score, a behind, came when a kick from Mick Grace hit the post.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy then had the advantage of the wind in the second quarter.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Goals to Mick Grace and Fred Fontaine had them ahead at half time.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Charlie Colgan gave South Melbourne the lead with the only goal of the third term.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Bill McSpeerin's goal 15 minutes into the final quarter gave Fitzroy the win.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy's Bert Sharpe, the team's centre half-forward in its 1898 premiership side, was a late withdrawal from the side due to the death of his father the day before the Grand Final; his teammates wore black armbands for that match.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-season] The **1899 VFL season** was the third season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 13 May to 16 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating South Melbourne by one point in the 1899 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's second (consecutive and overall) VFL premiership.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy also won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James won his second leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-season] In 1899, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-commission/1899-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1899 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-grand-final] The **1900 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Melbourne Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne on 22 September 1900.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-grand-final] It was the 3rd annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1900 VFL season.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 20,181 spectators, was won by Melbourne by a margin of 4 points.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-grand-final] The winner of this match would win the premiership.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-grand-final] Arthur Sowden, and Bill Bowe were unable to play for the Melbourne team, due to injury, and Eric Gardner was unavailable.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] The **1900 VFL season** was the fourth season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 5 May to 22 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] Melbourne won the premiership, defeating Fitzroy by four points in the 1900 VFL grand final; it was Melbourne's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] Fitzroy won its second consecutive minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] Geelong's Teddy Lockwood and Essendon's Albert Thurgood tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] In 1900, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves", although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1900 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] The rescheduling of round 3 until after round 14, which occurred following the cancellation of the originally scheduled matches due to heavy rain, is also reflected in this table.
[src:afl-commission/1900-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Fitzroy won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The **AFL Commission** is the board of directors that governs the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Its chairman has been Richard Goyder since 4 April 2017.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 1985, the AFL (then named Victorian Football League Limited) formed the commission as a body independent of its member clubs, to operate its competition.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over from the AFL's board of directors, who had been representatives of its then-15 member clubs.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council which had published the Laws of Australian Football.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL's constitution self-proclaims it to be the "keeper of the code" responsible for the sport of Australian football.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL operates the All-Australian team, World (formerly All-international) team and Australian Football Hall of Fame.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL operates the premier professional Australian Football competition in Australia and the State of Origin competition (1991-1999 and 2026-present).
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Since 1998, it has also overseen Australia's involvement in the International Rules Series.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] An independent governing body for the competition was first moved in December 1984 during the fallout of VFL president Allen Aylett's resignation following the South Melbourne Football Club's financially disastrous relocation to Sydney.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The club, managed from Melbourne but playing in Sydney, had sustained substantial finanical losses in Sydney and large loans had been written out by the league to keep them viable, which was also impacting the finances of the competition.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Under its first chief commissioner, Jack Hamilton, the VFL began a restructuring toward a franchise model, whereby member clubs operate licenses owned by the league.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The model helped make private ownership of the Swans possible in 1985, as well as the sale of new licenses, resulting in the entry of the Brisbane Bears and West Coast Eagles in 1987.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Under the new model, many Melbourne clubs struggling for financial viability such as St Kilda, Fitzroy and North Melbourne could be kept afloat by a combination of private ownership and league subsidies from the sale of new clubs and television rights.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The restructuring paved the way for the VFL's expansion into a national competition.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Despite continuing financial troubles at many clubs, including the Swans and Footscray, the AFL was able to turn the competition's finances around by 1989, aided by increased television rights and the sale of $4 million licenses to interstate expansion clubs.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 2014, all AFL players were fully-paid professionals for the first time in the competition's history.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL is governed by its board of directors, called the AFL Commission.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council, which ceased operations after 89 years of existence.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 2002, it took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 2010, it took over the operations of Women's Football Australia, which ceased operations in 2015.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL took over the operations of the New South Wales Australian Football League Limited, and the AFL subsidiary, AFL NSW/ACT now operates in Australia's most populous eastern state and the ACT.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL promotes and brands the sport under its own name rather than of the formal name of Australian Football.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are elected by the 18 AFL clubs, with each of the 18 clubs entitled to make nominations, but other Australian Football leagues, associations and clubs do not have any control or representation.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL approves new club franchise licenses to expand its competition.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Since 1987, it has been instrumental in the merger that created the Brisbane Lions, while the Sydney Swans were fully owned by the AFL, which retains a controlling interest and reversion rights in the event the Sydney Swans do not repay debts to the AFL.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL also fully owns the Greater Western Sydney Giants.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Other clubs to have an AFL appointed board include the Sydney Swans, the Gold Coast Suns, Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL operates a Competitive Balance Fund, which redistributes profits to the clubs most in need to help ensure that all of its member clubs are financially sustainable in the long-term.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL is financially dependent on the success of its competitions with the majority of its funding coming from the AFL competition broadcasting rights.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The 2025-2031 rights will earn $4.5 billion, the most lucrative in Australian sporting history.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL operates the Australian Football Hall of Fame, the AFL men's underage championships and AFL Women's underage championships.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] It is also responsible for senior State of Origin competition, which will return in 2026 after a 27-year hiatus.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL is administered by its commission of company directors, which sets policy and has directed the VFL/AFL (known then as the VFL) as the game's most professional league since December 1985.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over as the directors of the AFL from its Board of Directors, which had been appointed as delegates of its then 15 member clubs.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The Board of Directors voted itself out of existence, and the AFL's then 15 member clubs also voted to abolish the old system of club appointment of directors and to adopt a new Memorandum and Articles of Association for the AFL.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] This was a significant change of power: between 1985 and 1993, the VFL/AFL had required explicit approval by a 75% vote of its member teams for major items such as further expansion, mergers, relocations, and major capital works.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the ANFC (see Principle 2 below).
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL also created an international policy in 2005 and took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Amateur and semi-professional Australian Football competitions across Australia are mostly self-sufficient from the AFL.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] These competitions, their clubs and teams often buy equipment and apparel that is AFL branded which provides revenue to the AFL.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Some junior competitions pay to use the AFL proprietary Auskick program and junior clubs pay the AFL for give-away packs at AFL run promotions in their localities.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL has established a pathway that features junior Academies and scholarships from representational level up to its member clubs.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The highest level is the AFL Academy, with academies for each state being managed by their respective AFL clubs and affiliated governing bodies.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Between 2010 and 2021, the AFL spent between $6–38 million per annum (under 5% of total revenue) on game development grants globally (excluding a one-off COVID-19 Pandemic community football recovery package).
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] With a new TV rights deal in 2022 and to help the game at the grassroots continue its recovery post COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased its community grants to $67 million.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are nominated and elected by vote of the 18 AFL member clubs.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] A two-thirds majority of member clubs have the power to veto over commission decisions.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The commission elects its chairman and employs a chief executive officer to oversees the management and operations of the AFL.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] While the commission is responsible for directing AFL policy, it has, on occasions, become directly involved in on and off-field matters relating to AFL competitions, players, coaches and managers.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] Sometimes these interventions have been in controversial circumstances.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL owns a stake in the Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney clubs.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The AFL manages a special fund called the Competitive Balance Fund (CBF) since 2004 as a grant of up to $5 million per club to ensure that member clubs remain financially viable.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] The system was later changed to the Annual Special Distribution (ASD) of $6.3 million shared among all clubs, as well as allowing for grants and special concessions, such as payments, to ensure that the AFL member clubs remain viable in the short term.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In 2006, the AFL approved a $2.1 million special financial assistance package for Carlton.
[src:afl-commission/afl-commission] In early 2009, it increased Melbourne's assistance from $250,000 to $1 million and made a $1 million grant to Port Adelaide.
